NarNarrative: Sponges are filter feeders capturing nutrients from the water that would otherwise wash away in the current. Their bodies grow into shapes that reflect this lifestyle such as dramatic hollow columns, goblets and tubes. They suck in water through holes on the outside surface of their bodies and funnel it out through their centre like smoke from a chimney.

Corals are built by colonies of tiny animals (coral polyps) that use calcium carbonate to create hard, stony structures. In cup and star corals, the corallites (the individual cups in which the coral polyps grow) are large and often form swollen mounds or cups. In contrast, flower corals, form short branching colonies tipped with large corallites, resembling plants, from which they take their name.

Corals are built by colonies of tiny animals (coral polyps) that use calcium carbonate to create hard, stony structures. In cup and star corals, the corallites (the individual cups in which the coral polyps grow) are large and often form swollen mounds or cups. In contrast, flower corals, form short branching colonies tipped with large corallites, resembling plants, from which they take their name.

Where coral polyps split into pairs the colony forms a branching structure. These species of coral often grow into dramatic branching sheets and spires as the coral spreads up and out, creating some of the most recognisable and iconic reef habitats. The largest and most complex branching corals grow at the seaward edge of the reef, farthest from the shore.

The largest and most complex branching corals grow at the seaward edge of the reef, farthest from the shore.

The wrinkled appearance of these corals gives them their common name, brain corals.  These types of corals are formed when coral polyps only partially split and develop long chains of conjoined polyps that fold and wrinkle into massive, round structures. Brain corals live for many years and are slow growing. Their compact shape makes them resistant to rough conditions and predators.
